{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15423"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.26,0.15,0.15,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55522"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23509"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis. He has a history of alcohol dependence and drinks 120 gm of alcohol daily. He has no other medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. He has spider naevi on his chest, palmar erythema, and gynaecomastia. His abdomen is distended with a fluid thrill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 92 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelets 85 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ealbumin 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebilirubin 45 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ealanine transaminase 65 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Einternational normalised ratio 1.8 (0.9-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA liver biopsy is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological features is most characteristic of this patient\u0027s liver disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrous septa","Fatty change","Mallory bodies","Portal inflammation","Ballooning degeneration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of decompensated cirrhosis including portal hypertension (evidenced by variceal bleeding), ascites, and synthetic dysfunction (coagulopathy and hypoalbuminaemia). The clinical features and history of alcohol dependence suggest alcoholic liver disease as the underlying cause. The histology shows islands of hepatocytes (deeper pink) completely surrounded by fibrous tissue (paler pink).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrous septa\u003C/strong\u003E are the defining histological feature of cirrhosis. These bands of collagen divide the liver parenchyma into regenerative nodules, disrupting the normal hepatic architecture. This architectural distortion leads to portal hypertension and the clinical manifestations of cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty change\u003C/strong\u003E (steatosis) is an early finding in alcoholic liver disease but is not specific for cirrhosis. It may actually be less prominent in advanced cirrhosis as the disease progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallory bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are cytoplasmic inclusions found in alcoholic hepatitis, but they are not specific for cirrhosis and may be absent in advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in various liver diseases including viral hepatitis and autoimmune conditions. While it may be present in cirrhosis, it is not the defining feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBallooning degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E of hepatocytes is characteristic of alcoholic hepatitis but is not specific for cirrhosis. It represents cellular injury from alcohol toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe progression to cirrhosis involves complex mechanisms of liver injury, inflammation, and fibrosis. While various histological features may be present, the formation of fibrous septa and regenerative nodules is pathognomonic of cirrhosis, regardless of the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cirrhosis is characterised histologically by fibrous septa dividing the liver into regenerative nodules.","Portal hypertension develops due to distortion of hepatic architecture by fibrosis and nodule formation.","Laboratory features of cirrhosis include elevated transaminases, reduced albumin, and prolonged prothrombin time."],"references":["Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kurtovic E, Limaiem F. Mallory Bodies. 2024 Apr 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31424884","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55522"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21309"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21309"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Iga6GL6xhE1nPTKk2nmJCqb5QkaDrw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Iga6GL6xhE1nPTKk2nmJCqb5QkaDrw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":395}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55522"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T10:11:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T10:12:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8114"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"descriptio